  "plan_analysis": "The question hinges on how much the Google Trends daily value for the term \u201cethel kennedy\u201d moves in a 10-day window, with a \u00b13 band being classified as \u201cDoesn\u2019t change.\u201d  \nWhat forecasters already know:\n\u2022 The current (1 Mar 2026) 30-day-window value is 74.  \n\u2022 The resolution will use SerpApi\u2019s TIMESERIES endpoint for the US, fixed-scale dates 12 Feb\u201314 Mar 2026, and will compare the two single\u2013day values (04 Mar vs 14 Mar, UTC).  \n\nInformation gaps:\n1. Base-rate / historical volatility: How often has \u201cethel kennedy\u201d moved by >3 points in any 10-day span? Are large swings rare or common?  \n2. Resolution mechanics nuance: How noisy is the SerpApi daily data series itself? What is the typical jitter for a low-search-volume proper-name term?  \n3. Key short-term drivers: Is there any scheduled or breaking event in early-to-mid-March 2026 that could suddenly raise or lower search interest (e.g., health news, Kennedy-family legal developments, new documentary releases)?  \n4. Current state / trajectory: What are the exact daily values from mid-February to now? Are they trending up, down, or flat?  \n5. Contrarian possibilities: Rumours of death, viral social-media posts, or RFK-family political stories could create an unexpected spike; knowing whether anything like that is brewing is critical.\n\nSearch strategy:\n\u2022 Pull the full Google Trends time-series to eyeball volatility and recent trajectory.  \n\u2022 Look for prior spikes to understand catalysts (birthdays, anniversaries, obituaries, RFK Jr headlines, documentaries).  \n\u2022 Scan very recent news and upcoming-events coverage (Google News + AskNews) for any March 4-14 hooks.  \n\u2022 Study generic research on daily-level Google Trends noise to calibrate what a \u00b13 move means for a low-volume term.  \n\u2022 Use one Agent query to surface analyses of how often small Google Trends series move by >3 points in ten-day windows across comparable personal-name keywords (historical base rate).",
